<paragraph pageNumber="255">Discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageNumber="256" pageNumber="255">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:222191" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex ameliae De Souza, Soares &amp; Della Lucia" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ameliae">Acromyrmex ameliae</taxonomicName>
is a social parasite with much smaller reproductives (females and males) than those of its hosts (Table 1). Morphometrically, the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:222191" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex ameliae De Souza, Soares &amp; Della Lucia" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ameliae">A. ameliae</taxonomicName>
queen is not a simple miniature of its hosts' queens, like 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152549" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Myrmica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Myrmica microrubra Seifert" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="microrubra">Myrmica microrubra</taxonomicName>
and its host 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:32430" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Myrmica" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Myrmica rubra (Linnaeus)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rubra">Myrmica rubra</taxonomicName>
(Steiner et al., 2005). Here, we can distinguish the new species from the other of the group with propodeal spines: they are straight and laterally compressed unlike 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24767" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex subterraneus (Forel)" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subterraneus">subterraneus</taxonomicName>
subspecies where they are slight to strongly curved and conical. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:222191" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex ameliae De Souza, Soares &amp; Della Lucia" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ameliae">Acromyrmex ameliae</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152541" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex insinuator Schultz, Bekkevold &amp; Boomsma" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insinuator">A. insinuator</taxonomicName>
not only by its size (compare Tables 1 and 2) and color (brown dark against yellowish-orange) but as well it does not present a single strong median ruga extending from the central ocellus to the level of the posterior borders of lateral ocelli, like 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152541" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex insinuator Schultz, Bekkevold &amp; Boomsma" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insinuator">A. insinuator</taxonomicName>
. On the contrary, around its central ocellus, the cuticle is wholly rugous without a distinct median ruga. In 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:152541" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex insinuator Schultz, Bekkevold &amp; Boomsma" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="255" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insinuator">A. insinuator</taxonomicName>
the anteroventral edge of the postpetiole is broadly and evenly concave, without a broad median anteroventral extension. The anteroventral portion of the post-petiole in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:222191" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Acromyrmex" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Acromyrmex ameliae De Souza, Soares &amp; Della Lucia" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="256" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ameliae">A. ameliae</taxonomicName>
has irregular extensions, without the concavity present in the first species.
</paragraph>
